---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="The Three-Part Plantar Fasciitis Protocol | Practical Podiatrist">
  <article class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6 py-12 text-slate-300 relative z-10">
    <header class="mb-12 border-b border-white/10 pb-8">
      <span class="text-xs font-bold text-accent uppercase tracking-widest block mb-2">Advanced Treatment Guide</span>
      <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold tracking-tight text-white mb-4">The Three-Part Plantar Fasciitis Protocol</h1>
      <p class="text-lg text-slate-400">A complete biomechanical roadmap: Protect the tissue, drain the fluid, and control the chemical inflammatory cycle.</p>
    </header>

    <div class="space-y-8 text-base md:text-lg leading-relaxed">
      <p>
        Plantar fasciitis is an inflammatory condition that occurs where the plantar fascia—the thick band of connective tissue running along the bottom of your foot—inserts onto the <strong>calcaneus</strong> (the heel bone)[cite: 2442]. When the arches lack proper support for a given activity, the foot elongates, putting quick tension on this insertion point (almost like the plantar fascia is trying to tear off the heel bone)[cite: 2443].
      </p>

      <p>
        During rest, swelling and inflammation build up under the heel[cite: 2444]. When you take your first steps in the morning or after a long rest, you step directly onto the swollen area[cite: 2445]. This is what causes that sharp, stabbing pain[cite: 2446]. To get you pain-free, we must reduce the swelling under the heel, support the inflamed tissues, and reduce the amount of inflammation your body is making[cite: 2446].
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-white mt-8 border-l-4 border-teal-400 pl-3">Part 1: Protect the Injured and Inflamed Tissues</h2>
      <p>Your first priority is structural offloading[cite: 2418]. Depending on severity, protection scales from an immobilization orthopedic walking boot down to highly supportive shoes or shoes paired with firm over-the-counter orthotics[cite: 2420, 2421]. Avoid walking barefoot at home on hard floors entirely[cite: 2345].</p>

      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-white mt-8 border-l-4 border-teal-400 pl-3">Part 2: Reduce the Inflammation Locally (The Sponge Analogy)</h2>
      <p>Think of swollen soft tissue as a dense kitchen sponge[cite: 2423]. Squeezing it via deep manual massage before walking on it is mandatory to clear trapped fluid back into your circulation[cite: 2381, 2382, 2426]. Massage 4 times a day for 15-20 minutes until the heel feels better[cite: 2349]. If an emergency hits and you cannot massage first, use the <strong>Emergency Tiptoe Fallback</strong> to keep the fascia completely slack and prevent insertion tearing[cite: 2371, 2383, 2394].</p>

      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-white mt-8 border-l-4 border-teal-400 pl-3">Part 3: Prevent the Inflammation From Returning</h2>
      <p>Scale your chemical management depending on severity: Tier 1 Topicals (Voltaren Gel), Tier 2 Oral NSAIDs, Tier 3 Oral Steroid Taper (via PCP), or Tier 4 Injectable Steroids at a specialist's office[cite: 2431, 2432, 2433].</p>
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
